# Phase 5 — Event Bus

Magpie core acts as an event broker. Every command emits a named event with a JSON payload on completion. Plugins subscribe to events in their manifests — magpie invokes subscribers sequentially with the payload piped to stdin. Subscriber failures never block the original command.

## Learning Focus

- JSON serialization with `encoding/json`
- Building a static subscriber registry from installed plugin manifests
- Sequential subprocess dispatch with stdin piping

## Core Events

| Event | Emitted by |
|---|---|
| `vault.resolved` | any command |
| `inbox.captured` | `inbox capture` |
| `inbox.listed` | `inbox list` |
| `archive.added` | `archive add` |
| `log.appended` | `log append` |
| `lint.completed` | `lint` |
| `context.read` | `context status` |
| `plugin.installed` | `plugin install` |
| `plugin.removed` | `plugin remove` |

## You Drive

The subscriber registry — built from all installed plugin manifests at startup. Where does it live? How do you efficiently look up subscribers for a given event name without re-reading manifests on every command?

The subscriber invocation — `exec.Command` with stdin piped to the JSON payload. Subscriber failures go to stderr and execution continues. How do you time out a slow subscriber without blocking indefinitely?
